		7.1. Introduction to if
	.1.1. General
the if construction allows you to spesify different courses of acction depending on condition, with its syntax being:
	if TEST-COMMANDS; then CONSEQUENT-COMMANDS; fi
the TEST-COMMAND is usualy a numerical or sting comparison, but it can be any command that returns 0 if it succeds and any other if it fails
on the book there is a list of "primaries" used in TEST-COMMAND in between sqare brackets

the CONSEQUENT-COMMANDS can be any valid command
	
	.1.2. Simple application of if
the ? variable holds the exit status of the previously excecuted command

		7.2. More advanced if usage
	.2.1. if/then/else constructs
this is sed to give an alternative output if TEST-COMMANDS is false

	.2.2. if/then/elif/else constructs
this is the full form of the if statement:
	if TEST-COMMANDS1;then
	CONSEQUENT-COMMANDS;
	elif TEST-COMMANDS2;then
	CONSEQUENT-COMMANDS2;
	else ALTERANTE-COMMANDS;
	fi
only one of this consequent or alternate commands is excecuted, and the return status is the exis status of the last excecuted command or 0 if no condition is true

	.2.4. Boolean operations
the boolean operators "AND" (&&) and "OR" (||) can be used in our code to make it shorter

	.2.5. Using the exit statement
the exit statement terminates the execution of the entire script, this statement takes an otional argument, stored in $? that is the exit status code.
a zero means that it ran succesfully
	
